	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/08/29/morning-agenda-playing-the-tax-game/" data-title="Morning Agenda: Playing the Tax Game" data-description="American companies are finding new ways to avoid paying taxes. | Dueling scholarship funds in China. | Detecting fraud in China may be riskier than committing it. | Consumers get some relief at the gas pump.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">BUSINESSES WINNING THE TAX GAME <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Across corporate America, companies large and small are finding new ways to avoid paying taxes, making it harder than ever for the federal government to replenish its already depleted coffers, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/08/28/businesses-find-ways-to-avoid-corporate-taxes-but-a-fix-seems-unlikely">DealBookâs David Gelles writes</a></b>. As a result, business income tax revenue remains stagnant at about 2 percent of gross domestic product even as corporate profits hit records. Business taxes now make up less than 10 percent of federal revenue, down sharply from the years after World War II, when about 30 percent of federal revenue came from corporate taxes.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe decline is the result of the <b>rise of untraditional business structures</b>, the effects of a more globalized economy and a labyrinth of subsidies and tax credits,â Mr. Gelles writes. The surging popularity of inversions â acquisitions of overseas companies that allow United States corporations to reincorporate abroad â is raising particular concerns. Master limited partnership are also being exploited now more than ever, as are real estate investment trusts. Washington is paying attention to these tax-avoidance techniques, but the more fundamental issue is a <b>series of systemic changes to the tax system</b> and the shifting international tax landscape, Mr. Gelles writes.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">DUELING SCHOLARSHIP FUNDS IN CHINA <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Higher education has a new trans-Pacific rivalry, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/08/28/in-china-dueling-scholarship-programs-from-billionaires">Keith Bradsher writes in DealBook</a></b>. Stephen A. Schwarzman, the chairman and chief executive of the private equity firm Blackstone Group, gave $100 million last year to start a one-year graduate program at Beijingâs Tsinghua University modeled on the Rhodes Scholar program at Oxford. By last month, he had raised $200 million more from other donors. But one of his prospective donors in China has responded to Mr. Schwarzmanâs appeals by <b>setting up another scholarship program</b> to send Chinese students to the United States.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Schwarzman approached Zhang Xin, the chief executive of SOHO China, when they both attended the World Economic Forum last January in Davos, Switzerland. Instead of giving money to Mr. Schwarzmanâs program, she and her husband, Pan Shiyi, the chairman of SOHO China, decided to pledge $100 million from their companyâs charitable foundation to American universities to <b>bankroll need-based scholarships for Chinese students</b>. Mr. Schwarzman said he did not mind the decision by Ms. Zhang and Mr. Pan to set up a scholarship fund instead of supporting his.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> RISKS OF DETECTING CHINESE FRAUDS  <span class="divider"> | </span></span> âIt can be very risky to do things in China that are taken for granted in other countries,â <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/29/business/in-china-detecting-fraud-riskier-than-doing-it.html?ref=business">Floyd Norris writes in the High &#038; Low Finance column</a></b>. Kun Huang, a Chinese-born Canadian citizen, spent two years in a Chinese jail for contributing to research that led his employer to recommend short sales of Silvercorp Metals, a silver producer that is based in Canada but does its mining in China.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Huang, who had been hired by the hedge fund Eos, eventually <b>gained a reputation for spotting Chinese frauds</b>, which he publicized online under the name Alfred Little. One of his reports questioned whether Silvercorp had exaggerated the mineâs production. Mr. Huang was subsequently arrested, terrorized and prohibited from leaving China. âMany of the frauds that have come to light in recent years have involved lies that would have been obvious if documents filed with Chinese government agencies had been analyzed by underwriters, auditors and analysts involved with the companies,â Mr. Norris writes. âBut China has shown <b>more hostility to those who found the frauds</b> than to those who committed them.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Data on <b>personal income and outlays</b> is released at 8:30 a.m. The Thomson Reuters/University of Michigan <b>consumer sentiment index</b> for August is released at 9:55 a.m. A happy birthday to Treasury Secretary Jacob J. Lew. Happy birthday as well to Warren E. Buffett, who turns 84 on Saturday.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> RELIEF AT THE GAS PUMP <span class="divider"> | </span></span> With the Labor Day weekend approaching, travelers may find themselves with some extra change in their pockets. Despite recent global turmoil, oil prices â and those at the pump â are easing, <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/29/business/energy-environment/shale-oil-in-texas-keeps-gas-prices-affordable.html?ref=business">Clifford Krauss writes in The New York Times</a></b>. The national average price for a gallon of regular gasoline was $3.43 on Thursday, according to the AAA motor club, nearly a dime lower than a month ago.  Energy and travel analysts project the lowest gasoline prices this holiday weekend of any Labor Day since 2010, and the highest level of motor travel since 2008. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">United States <b>refinery production reached record highs</b> in recent weeks and left supply depots flush, cushioning the impact of all the instability surrounding traditional global oil fields, Mr. Krauss writes. And <b>nowhere is the boom bigger than in Texas</b>, home to two of three of the nationâs biggest shale-oil drilling frenzies. Oil rushes are nothing new to the state, Mr. Krauss writes, but the new bonanza has doubled the stateâs crude production over the last two years, suddenly making Texas a bigger producer than either Kuwait or Venezuela.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Consumers may be relieved, but another oil-related event is likely to rankle environmentalists. On Thursday, Royal Dutch Shell submitted a plan to the federal government to try once again to <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/29/business/shell-submits-a-plan-for-new-alaskan-arctic-oil-exploration.html?ref=business">explore for oil in the Alaskan Arctic</a></b>. Shellâs proposed programs consist of two drilling rigs working simultaneously in the Chukchi Sea, which could produce more than 400,000 barrels of oil a day.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>In observance of Labor Day, there will be no DealBook newsletter on Monday. Weâll be back on Tuesday. For the latest in breaking news and analysis in the world of finance, please visit: <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/">dealbook.nytimes.com</a></em>.</p>
</div>
